
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Predictors of the Performance of Project Groups in R & D Organizations
AU  - Keller, Robert T.
Y1  - 1986/12/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255941
DO  - 10.5465/255941
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 715
EP  - 726
VL  - 29
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Results from 32 project groups in a large R&D organization showed that group cohesiveness, physical distance, job satisfaction, and innovative orientation were associated with performance of projects. Hierarchical regression analyses revealed that group cohesiveness accounted for unique variance in four performance criteria, both contemporaneously and one year later. An innovative orientation added unique variance to the quality of projects as rated initially by group members and as rated by management one year later. Type of R&D moderated the relationship between innovative orientation and members' ratings of project quality, in that a significant relationship was found for research projects, but not for projects engaged in product development or technical service.
AB  - Results from 32 project groups in a large R&D organization showed that group cohesiveness, physical distance, job satisfaction, and innovative orientation were associated with performance of projects. Hierarchical regression analyses revealed that group cohesiveness accounted for unique variance in four performance criteria, both contemporaneously and one year later. An innovative orientation added unique variance to the quality of projects as rated initially by group members and as rated by management one year later. Type of R&D moderated the relationship between innovative orientation and members' ratings of project quality, in that a significant relationship was found for research projects, but not for projects engaged in product development or technical service.
