T1  - On the Causal Ordering of Job Satisfaction and Organizational Commitment
AU  - Curry, James P.
AU  - Wakefield, Douglas S.
AU  - Price, James L.
AU  - Mueller, Charles W.
Y1  - 1986/12/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255951
DO  - 10.5465/255951
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 847
EP  - 858
VL  - 29
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this article the authors discuss research they have conducted that examines the relationship between job satisfaction and organizational commitment. They briefly discuss the definitions of each concept, noting that satisfaction and commitment have been linked to employees' rates of absenteeism and turnover. They note that previous studies have indicated that one's level of satisfaction will determine their level of commitment; however, they assert that the opposite may be true and that finding the correct ordering of these variables has both theoretical and practical implications. They assert that if the correct ordering is found employers would better understand how to enact incentive programs to increase the commitment of their employees.
AB  - In this article the authors discuss research they have conducted that examines the relationship between job satisfaction and organizational commitment. They briefly discuss the definitions of each concept, noting that satisfaction and commitment have been linked to employees' rates of absenteeism and turnover. They note that previous studies have indicated that one's level of satisfaction will determine their level of commitment; however, they assert that the opposite may be true and that finding the correct ordering of these variables has both theoretical and practical implications. They assert that if the correct ordering is found employers would better understand how to enact incentive programs to increase the commitment of their employees.
